Two points $(c, d, e),(x, y, z) \in \mathbb{R}^3$ , we say that the midpoint of these two points is the point with coordinates $\left(\frac{c+x}{2}
,
\frac{d+y}{2}
,
\frac{e+z}{2}\right)$ Take any set $S$ of nine points from $\mathbb{R}^3$ with integer coordinates. Prove that there must be at least one pair of points
  in $S$ whose midpoint also has integer coordinates. I've tried to do an example with set $$S=\{(2,2,2),(1,8,2),(3,4,5),(5,2,2),(4,2,9),\\(2,1,4),(6,8,2),(0,0,0),(5,2,3)\}$$ So taking $2$ points, $(3,4,5)$ and $(5,2,3)$ so $(3+5)/2=4$ , $(4+2)/2=3$ , $(5+3)/2 = 4$ , which are integers. I'm wanting this argument to hold in general and I'm finding it tricky to prove this does anyone have suggestions would be grateful!
